Figure \ref{huberpl} examines the behavior of the LDA index on two 2D simulated data sets, using a Huber plot~\citep{huber1990data}, that is also available in the \texttt{PPtreeViz} package~\citep{PPtreeViz}. The projection pursuit index values are calculated for all 1D projections of the 2D data, by parametrizing the projections using an angle $\theta$. The projection vectors are generated using ($cos~\theta$, $sin~\theta$), for $\theta$ = $1^{\circ}$, . . . , $180^{\circ}$. The index value is computed by projecting the data  accordingly, and displayed as a line (solid) winding around the data scatterplot. The circle (dashed line) is a guideline, and corresponds to the median of all index values. The projection vector producing the maximum index value is indicated as a dotted line, and the corresponding projected data is shown in the density plot (right). The first data set (top row) was simulated without separation between the classes, and this is reflected by a fairly uniform index function, that is close to the median for all projections. The best separation simply reflects sampling variability that one group (green) is slightly shifted farther afield than the other two classes. The second data set (bottom row) has separated classes visible in a 1D projection, and each class has strong correlation between the two variables. The LDA index is smooth, varying substantially with projection, with a flattish peak at the optimal projection. The LDA index easily finds the separation between these classes.
 
The PDA index is useful when $n$ is small relative to $p$ and when the variables are highly correlated. In these situations the maximum likelihood variance-covariance matrix estimator will be close to singular, affecting the inverse calculation. The PDA index adjusts the variance-covariance matrix calculation, as follows:


\begin{equation}
\mathbb{I}_{PDA}(\blA,\lambda)=1-\frac{|\blA^T \blW_{PDA}(\lambda)\blA|}{|\blA^T (\blW_{PDA}(\lambda)+\blB) \blA|}
\end{equation}

\noindent where notation is the same as for the LDA index, with the addition of $\lambda \in [0,1)$ is a shrinkage parameter, and a different within group sum of squares, $\blW_{PDA}(\lambda)=\mbox{diag}(\blW)+(1-\lambda)\mbox{offdiag}(\blW)$.


