\subsection{PPF Algorithm }

A projection pursuit classification random forest can be defined as a collection of randomized projection pursuit classification trees $\{ h(\mathbf{x}, \Theta_k), k = 1, \cdots, B$\} defined in subsection \ref{PPFdef}. The PPtree algorithm underlying PPF was mentioned before. In this subsection PPF algorithm is described.

\begin{enumerate}

\item
$B$ stratified bootstrap samples from $d_n$ are taken. For each group, $n_g$ cases are re-sampled from $d_{n_g}=\{(\mathbf{x}_i, y_i)| y_i = g, i=1, \cdots, n\}$ (training data set for group $g$) independently and uniformly. We denote this $k$th bootstrap sample from $g$th group as $b_{k_g}$. The $k$th bootstrap sample $b_k=\{b_{k_g}:g=1, \cdots, G\}$.

\item Use a bootstrap sample $b_k$ to grow a randomized PPtree $(h(\mathbf{x}, \Theta_k))$ (Note that the depth of the PPtree is at most $G-1$, where $G$ is the number of classes).

\begin{enumerate}
\item Start with all the cases in $b_k$ in the root node.
\item Select $m$ predictor variables from the data in the node where $m<<p$. 
\item Find the optimal one-dimensional projection $\pmb{a_1}^*$ to separate all the classes in $b_k$.
\item If more than two class, then reduce the number of classes to two by comparing means, and assign new labels, $g_1^*$ and $g_2^*$ to each case (called the new response $y_i^*$ in $b_k$).
\item Find the optimal one-dimensional projection, $\pmb{a_1}^{**}$, using $b_k$ with selected $m$ variables and the relabeled response, $y^*$, to separate $g_1^*$ and $g_2^*$.
The linear combination is computed by optimizing a projection pursuit index to get a projection of the variables that best separates the classes using the $m$ randomly selected variables. Two index options are available LDA or PDA.
\item Compute the decision boundary $c$ (see PPtree algorithm above).
\item Keep $\pmb{a_1}^{**}$ and $c$.
\item Separate the data into two groups using the new labels $g_1^*$ and $g_2^*$ and assign $g_1^*$ to the left node and $g_2^*$  to the right node.
\item Repeat from (b) to (h) if $g_1^*$ or $g_2^*$ have more than two original classes.
\end{enumerate}
\item Repeat 2 for $k = 1,\ldots, B$.
\item The output is the ensemble of randomized PPtrees, $\{h(\mathbf{x}, \Theta_k)\}_{k=1}^B$.
\end{enumerate}



