\subsection{Parameter selection}

The primary parameters for PPF are mostly the same as those for RF: number of trees, and number of variables used in each node partition, with the addition of $\lambda$ when the PDA index is used.

Figure \ref{parameters} (left) shows the effect of proportion of variables for the benchmark data comparison. The average error over 200 training/test splits is shown. Generally, the error is lower when the more variables are used. For leukemia and NCI60, the error increases when more variables are included. These two examples are both small $n$, big $p$ data, which suggests that increasing the number of variables will be not the best strategy to reduce error. Section \ref{rnaapli} illustrates this.

Figure \ref{parameters} (right) compares  PPF and RF on the number of trees needed to optimize the oob error for the lymphoma data. Both need around 100 trees to produce best performance.

